:"1405","Norton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Norton, Suffolk, England":"Norton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Nedging, Suffolk, England":"Nedging, Suffolk, England","Bury St. Edmunds, Suffolk, England":"Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England","Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England":"Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Woodward","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a forester employed to look after the trees and game in a forest, Middle English <i>woodward</i> (from Old English <i>wudu</i> ‘wood’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guardian, protector’).","History: Henry Woodward emigrated from England in 1635 and settled first in Dorchester, MA, and subsequently in Northampton, MA. He had many prominent descendants. Another Henry Woodward, born <i>c.</i> 1646 in the British West Indies, was the first English settler in SC (1664)."],"variants":[{"name":"Woodard","meanings":["from the Norman Old French personal name <i>Odard</i>, <i>Udard</i>, Middle English <i>Wodard</i>, <i>Wudard</i>. It derives from the ancient Germanic name <i>Authard</i>, <i>Othard</i>, <i>Odard</i>, composed of the elements <i>aud-</i> ‘riches' + <i>hard-</i> ‘hard, bold’.","occupational name from Middle English <i>wode</i> ‘wood’ + <i>herde</i> ‘herd’ (Old English <i>wudu</i> + <i>hierde</i>), for a person who tended animals pastured in woodland.","post-medieval pronunciation of   Woodward  ."]},{"name":"Woodworth","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Woodward   or <b>Wadworth</b>, the latter being a habitational name from Wadworth in Yorkshire, which is derived from the Old English personal name <i>Wada</i>, <i>Wadda</i> + Old English <i>worth</i> ‘enclosure’."]},{"name":"Woodman","meanings":["English:","occupational name for a woodcutter or a forester (compare   Woodward  ), from Middle English <i>wodeman</i> ‘woodman’. In some instances this may be a variant of   Wadman  .","from the Middle English personal name <i>Wudemann</i> (Old English <i>Wuduman</i>, from <i>wudu</i> ‘wood’ + <i>mann</i> ‘man’)."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":21,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Woodward was born in 1434, in Norton, Suffolk, England, her father, Henry Woodward, was 32 and her mother, Elizabeth Mather, was 29. She married John Munning about 1455, in Norton, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1478, in Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England, at the age of 44, and was buried in Nedging, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"1434–1478":"1434–1478","1430–1486":"1430–1486","1456–1521":"1456–1521","1464–Male":"1464–Surnud","1472–1540":"1472–1540","1402–1492":"1402–1492","1405–1500":"1405–1500","1472":"1472","1492":"1492","from 1435 to 1492":"1435 kuni 1492","1435":"1435","1402":"1402","1434":"1434","1456":"1456","1478":"1478","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1521":"1521","1464":"1464","1486":"1486","1540":"1540","1430":"1430","about 1455":"umbes 1455","about 1432":"umbes 1432","1405":"1405","Norton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norton, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Norton, Suffolk, England":"Norton, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Nedging, Suffolk, England":"Nedging, Suffolk, England","Bury St. Edmunds, Suffolk, England":"Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England","Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England":"Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1434–1478":"1434–1478","1430–1486":"1430–1486","1456–1521":"1456–1521","1464–Male":"1464–Kuollut","1472–1540":"1472–1540","1402–1492":"1402–1492","1405–1500":"1405–1500","1472":"1472","1492":"1492","from 1435 to 1492":"vuodesta 1435 vuoteen 1492","1435":"1435","1402":"1402","1434":"1434","1456":"1456","1478":"1478","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1521":"1521","1464":"1464","1486":"1486","1540":"1540","1430":"1430","about 1455":"noin 1455","about 1432":"noin 1432","1405":"1405","Norton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norton, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Norton, Suffolk, England":"Norton, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Nedging, Suffolk, England":"Nedging, Suffolk, En